    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1870-09-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1870-09-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="179"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d179">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">No. 179.</note>
                <head>
                    <persName type="from">Mr. Fish</persName> to <persName type="to">Baron
                        Gerolt</persName>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>DEPARTMENT OF STATE,<hi rend="italic"> Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1870-09-16">
                            <hi rend="italic">September</hi> 16, 1870.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to inclose, for your information
                    and that of your government, a copy of a dispatch of the 22d ultimo, No. 266,
                    and of the papers which accompanied it, from E. B. Washburne, esq., the minister
                    of the United States at Paris, and who is charged with the protection of
                    subjects of North Germany in France, in relation to the expulsion of such
                    subjects from that country.</p>
                <p>I have the honor to be, with the highest consideration, sir, your obedient
                    servant,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>HAMILTON FISH.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>[This inclosure will be found in Mr. Washburne’s No. 266, dated 22d August,
                        1870, <hi rend="italic">ante,</hi> “France.”]</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
